-- #943 near-miss (S0 soundness hole with NO gate coverage until this fixture): an
-- OFF-SPINE, CLOSED-LABELED, COVARIANT effect over-performance in a CROSS-MODULE
-- generic-DEFAULT interface method body. `impl Mk Dog` in THIS module inherits the
-- default `mk` from lib/offspine_closed_launder_iface.mdk without overriding it --
-- exercising the cross-module default-method-inheritance path specifically (a
-- single-file fixture cannot distinguish "default inherited across a module
-- boundary" from "default inherited in the same file").
--
-- `mk`'s own declared arrow (`a -> (..., ...)`) carries NO effect row -- the
-- <Stdout> annotation is nested one level down, on the arrow inside the returned
-- tuple's first component. `fstOf` extracts that component and re-types it as pure
-- <Stdout> at the use site; if the launder escaped, calling it here would silently
-- perform the undeclared <Stderr> through a value the type system believes is
-- <Stdout>-only.
--
-- Verified 2026-07-24 on a fresh native build: check rejects with a LOCATED
-- diagnostic in lib/offspine_closed_launder_iface.mdk -- T-EFFECT-LEAK: "Effectful
-- value used where <Stdout> is allowed, but it performs <Stderr>" -- never a runtime
-- panic. (Note: T-EFFECT-LEAK, not T-EFFECT-LAUNDER -- see the PR description for
-- why that matters.)
--
-- Discriminating control (confirms this is genuinely off-spine, not redundant with
-- an already-covered on-spine case): moving the SAME launder onto the method's own
-- arrow spine (`m2 : a -> <Stdout> Int`, body performs <Stdout, Stderr>) is rejected
-- too, but via the DIFFERENT, already-gated diagnostic T-EFFECT-LAUNDER ("Default
-- body of '...' launders an effect ..."), not T-EFFECT-LEAK -- proving the off-spine
-- path is a genuinely distinct check that had no prior fixture.
import lib.offspine_closed_launder_iface.{Mk(..), mk}

data Dog = Dog

impl Mk Dog where


fstOf : Mk a => a -> (Unit -> <Stdout> Unit)
fstOf x = match mk x
  (f, _) => f

main =
  let f = fstOf Dog
  f ()
